The server was friendly but put our order in wrong and brought two completely different dishes without the appetizer. To make up for the mixup and additional wait, we were given our choice of a free dessert. We chose pecan pie and it was hands down the worst pecan pie I've ever had. I came here on a recommendation from someone who I know to have good taste in food, now I have to wonder what they were smoking when they ate here and thought they enjoyed it. Maybe it's changed and gone down in quality, I don't know, but I won't be coming back.

Occasionally, restaurants will brand or otherwise customize the standard wax paper that so often forms a barrier between onion rings and the plating. Remoulade follows this trend, with lines and lines of "remoulade" cover the paper. It shows a decent degree of effort and branding. The light red plastic basket is about as standard as they come.  The onion rings themselves are clearly hand battered, with a sliding shade of light to dark golden brown in color. The cracks in the facade are readily seen, as there is little solidity in the batter, with gaps and lack of full coating aplenty. The onions seem relatively thin cut, based on the size and thickness of the rings, but the batter looks cracked and weak.  While the batter wasn't quite as flavorful as its New Orleans companion, Saint Lawrence, I tasted a good blend of seasonings with some Cajun kick. The onion taste was relatively mild, but certainly present and flavorful. The light onion taste meshed well with the Cajun seasonings, which melded together to deliver a flavor sensation worthy of Bourbon Street, minus the drunken bead-grasping hordes, strippers, and tarot women preying on the previously mentioned hordes.  Overall, the flavor was cohesive, buttery, and smooth. I would have liked more onion taste, and I suspect the light taste was largely a result of the thin-cut onions, in addition to them being ever-so-slightly underdone. Despite these flaws, Remoulade delivered a solid, buttery, lightly greased onion ring. The combination was light and airy, and seemed to melt in my mouth.  Though the batter was a little gnarly, with peaks and valleys forming out of the not-so-delicately latticed coating, it made for a good crunch. The twin preys of slippage and shedding failed to rear their ugly faces, which is a remarkable achievement, especially given the tenuous grasp the batter had on the onion interior.  The onions themselves, as noted above, were a little under-done in most of the onion rings. Texture-wise, this typically results in a firm onion interior. While avoiding the plague of mushy, juicy onions is a positive step, the underdone onions usually mean less onion flavor, and a bit too hard of a bite. The inconsistency of the breading, and the curious presence of some nearly burnt batter (oddly contrasting with the lightly done onion rings) make these onion rings miss the mark.  In an area famous for tourism and drunken revelry, I naturally expected a steep price tag on any onion rings. I was pleasantly surprised to pay a mere $4.95 for a good sized basket of pretty good onion rings.

Wish I could give this review zero stars. My family and I had a very bad experience with the hostess at Remoulade. We are frequent visitors to New Orleans. We were in town with our 3 teenage children and my adult niece, and wanted to end our weekend with a fun dinner in the French Quarter. My niece was visiting New Orleans for only the 2nd time. We’ve been to Remoulade before and despite its location on Bourbon Street, we’ve always found it to be family-friendly and reasonably-priced with an authentic New Orleans charm. On the way to Remoulade, we passed several restaurants with long lines, so we were pleased to find only a 25-minute wait. After standing around for a few minutes, my niece and I got stools at the bar and the kids got chairs by the door. My husband stood with us at the bar. There are only about 12 seats at the bar and 5 chairs by the door, and counting those standing, about 20 people waiting. We had one round at the bar (I drank a soda) and watched several parties get seated. After about 45 minutes my niece went to check with the hostess and found that she had crossed our name out and seated several parties that came in after us. When my niece asked the hostess her why she had crossed our name off, she started yelling at my niece, saying she had called our name but no one answered. It’s very odd that not one of our party of 6 heard our name called, but we all heard her yell at my niece. Why didn’t the hostess walk 5 steps from her hostess stand and repeat our name when we didn’t answer the first time? How hard is it to keep track of 20 or so people waiting for a table? Didn’t she notice there were 3 underage young people sitting right in front of her by the door for 45 minutes? A decent host should notice a party that has been waiting a long time and come check on them. She should never yell at them! My niece asked her to put our name back on the list, and a few minutes later, this hostess looked right at me, muttered our name unintelligibly, and then loudly called our name so the whole restaurant could hear. We were seated and I told the waitress I would like to speak to the manager on duty. Wouldn’t you know, that hostess was the manager too. I waved her away and told her if she was the manager I didn’t want to speak to her. She again repeated that she called our name and we didn’t answer. I said “You yelled at my niece.” She said she did not. I told her that in her own mind, maybe she called our name, and she didn’t yell at my niece, but no one in my family heard our name and we all heard her yell. At that point they sent another employee over who said she was also a manager, but for all I know she was another server. This “manager” and our server apologized to us and were very nice, but our night had already been ruined by the rude hostess. We decided to leave even though it was 9:00 by then and we would have to go somewhere else and wait again. We left our server a $5 tip for her trouble, even though she didn’t serve us anything.
